text:
He was a man when He was hanging on Calvary, when they give Him the greatest tribute they ever did. When they said, "He saved others, He cannot save Himself." What a wonderful tribute, or compliment, they paid Him. If He saved these others, Himself, He couldn't save others. So He had to give Himself in order to save others. He was a man when He cried for mercy, when He said, "My God, my God, why hast thou forsaken Me?" He died like a man. Yes.
But when He rose on Easter morning, He proved He was God. No wonder the prophet said:
Living, He loved me; dying, He saved me;
Buried, He carried my sins far away;
Rising, He justified freely forever;
Someday He's coming, O glorious day.
Hallelujah. I love Him. Don't you? Walk in God's provided way.

text_no:
Han var et menneske da Han hang på Golgata, da de ga Ham den største hyllesten de noen gang ga. De sa: "Han frelste andre, men seg selv kan Han ikke frelse." For en fantastisk hyllest, eller kompliment, de ga Ham. For å frelse andre, måtte Han gi seg selv. Han var et menneske da Han ropte om nåde og sa: "Min Gud, min Gud, hvorfor har Du forlatt Meg?" Han døde som et menneske. Ja.
Men da Han stod opp påskemorgen, beviste Han at Han var Gud. Ikke rart at profeten sa:
Levde, Han elsket meg; døde, Han frelste meg;
Begravet, bar Han mine synder langt bort;
Stod opp, Han rettferdiggjorde fritt for evig;
En dag kommer Han igjen, O herlige dag.
Halleluja. Jeg elsker Ham. Gjør ikke du? Vandrer i Guds tilrettelagte vei.
